escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Fun=
ction of the observed sample results</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be co=
nfused with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-factor" title=3D=
"P-factor">P-factor</a>.</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testi=
ng" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">null-hyp=
othesis significance testing</a>, the <b><i>p</i>-value</b><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value=
#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 1<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Probability" title=3D"Probability">probability</a> of obtaining test res=
ults at least as extreme as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Re=
alization_(probability)" title=3D"Realization (probability)">result actuall=
y observed</a>, under the assumption that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a> =
is correct.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-ASA_=
4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#c=
ite_note-ASA-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> A very small <i>p</i>-value means that such an e=
xtreme observed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outcome_(probabili=
ty)" title=3D"Outcome (probability)">outcome</a> would be very unlikely <i>=
under the null hypothesis</i>. Even though reporting <i>p</i>-values of sta=
tistical tests is common practice in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Academic_publishing" title=3D"Academic publishing">academic publications=
</a> of many quantitative fields, misinterpretation and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misuse_of_p-values" title=3D"Misuse of p-values">misu=
se of p-values</a> is widespread and has been a major topic in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metascience" title=3D"Met=
ascience">metascience</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/P-value#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>In 2016, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Stati=
stical_Association" title=3D"American Statistical Association">American Sta=
tistical Association</a> (ASA) made a formal statement that "<i>p</i>-value=
s do not measure the probability that the studied hypothesis is true, or th=
e probability that the data were produced by random chance alone" and that =
"a <i>p</i>-value, or statistical significance, does not measure the size o=
f an effect or the importance of a result" or "evidence regarding a model o=
r hypothesis".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> That said, a 2019 ta=
sk force by ASA has issued a statement on statistical significance and repl=
icability, concluding with: "<i>p</i>-values and significance tests, when p=
roperly applied and interpreted, increase the rigor of the conclusions draw=
n from data".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ASA2019_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-ASA2019-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
