</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Usage">Usage</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DP-value&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Usage"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <i>p</i>-value is widely used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statis=
tical hypothesis testing">statistical hypothesis testing</a>, specifically =
in null hypothesis significance testing. In this method, before conducting =
the study, one first chooses a model (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a>) and=
 the alpha level <i>=CE=B1</i> (most commonly 0.05). After analyzing the da=
ta, if the <i>p</i>-value is less than <i>=CE=B1</i>, that is taken to mean=
 that the observed data is sufficiently inconsistent with the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null=
 hypothesis</a> for the null hypothesis to be rejected. However, that does =
not prove that the null hypothesis is false. The <i>p</i>-value does not, i=
n itself, establish probabilities of hypotheses. Rather, it is a tool for d=
eciding whether to reject the null hypothesis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nature506=
_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value=
#cite_note-nature506-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Misuse">Misuse</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DP-value&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Misuse"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misuse_of_p-values" =
title=3D"Misuse of p-values">Misuse of p-values</a></div>
<p>According to the ASA, there is widespread agreement that <i>p</i>-values=
 are often misused and misinterpreted.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ASA_4-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-ASA-=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> One practice that has been particularly criticized is accepti=
ng the alternative hypothesis for any <i>p</i>-value nominally less than 0.=
05 without other supporting evidence. Although <i>p</i>-values are helpful =
in assessing how incompatible the data are with a specified statistical mod=
el, contextual factors must also be considered, such as "the design of a st=
udy, the quality of the measurements, the external evidence for the phenome=
non under study, and the validity of assumptions that underlie the data ana=
lysis".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ASA_4-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-ASA-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Another concern i=
s that the <i>p</i>-value is often misunderstood as being the probability t=
hat the null hypothesis is true.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ASA_4-3" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-ASA-4"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i>p</i>-values and sign=
ificance tests also say nothing about the possibility of drawing conclusion=
s from a sample to a population.
</p><p>Some statisticians have proposed abandoning <i>p</i>-values and focu=
sing more on other inferential statistics,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ASA_4-4" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-=
ASA-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confiden=
ce_intervals" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confidence intervals">confiden=
ce intervals</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-val=
ue#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likel=
ihood_principle#The_law_of_likelihood" title=3D"Likelihood principle">likel=
ihood ratios</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-val=
ue#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba=
yes_factors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bayes factors">Bayes factors</a=
>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-2=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but there is heat=
ed debate on the feasibility of these alternatives.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_n=
ote-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Others have =
suggested to remove fixed significance thresholds and to interpret <i>p</i>=
-values as continuous indices of the strength of evidence against the null =
hypothesis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cit=
e_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Yet others suggested to report alongside <i>p</i>-va=
lues the prior probability of a real effect that would be required to obtai=
n a false positive risk (i.e. the probability that there is no real effect)=
 below a pre-specified threshold (e.g. 5%).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-29">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>That said, in 2019 a task force by ASA had convened to consider the =
use of statistical methods in scientific studies, specifically hypothesis t=
ests and <i>p</i>-values, and their connection to replicability.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-ASA2019_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/P-value#cite_note-ASA2019-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It states that "Different m=
easures of uncertainty can complement one another; no single measure serves=
 all purposes", citing <i>p</i>-value as one of these measures. They also s=
tress that <i>p</i>-values can provide valuable information when considerin=
g the specific value as well as when compared to some threshold. In general=
, it stresses that "<i>p</i>-values and significance tests, when properly a=
pplied and interpreted, increase the rigor of the conclusions drawn from da=
ta".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Calculation">Calculation</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DP-value&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Calculation"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Usually, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
style T}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>T</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle T}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ec7200acd984a1d3a3d7dc455e262fbe54f7f6e0" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.636ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle T}"=
></span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_statistic" titl=
e=3D"Test statistic">test statistic</a>. A test statistic is the output of =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_(mathematics)" title=3D"S=
calar (mathematics)">scalar</a> function of all the observations. This stat=
istic provides a single number, such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/T-statistic" title=3D"T-statistic"><i>t</i>-statistic</a> or an <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-test" title=3D"F-test"><i>F</i>-sta=
tistic</a>. As such, the test statistic follows a distribution determined b=
y the function used to define that test statistic and the distribution of t=
he input observational data.
</p><p>For the important case in which the data are hypothesized to be a ra=
ndom sample from a normal distribution, depending on the nature of the test=
 statistic and the hypotheses of interest about its distribution, different=
 null hypothesis tests have been developed. Some such tests are the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-test" title=3D"Z-test"><i>z</i>-test</a=
> for hypotheses concerning the mean of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribut=
ion</a> with known variance, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
-test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"T-test"><i>t</i>-test</a> based on <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-distribution" title=3D=
"Student's t-distribution">Student's <i>t</i>-distribution</a> of a suitabl=
e statistic for hypotheses concerning the mean of a normal distribution whe=
n the variance is unknown, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-t=
est" title=3D"F-test"><i>F</i>-test</a> based on the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/F-distribution" title=3D"F-distribution"><i>F</i>-distri=
bution</a> of yet another statistic for hypotheses concerning the variance.=
 For data of other nature, for instance, categorical (discrete) data, test =
statistics might be constructed whose null hypothesis distribution is based=
 on normal approximations to appropriate statistics obtained by invoking th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"=
Central limit theorem">central limit theorem</a> for large samples, as in t=
he case of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson%27s_chi-squared=
_test" title=3D"Pearson's chi-squared test">Pearson's chi-squared test</a>.
</p><p>Thus computing a <i>p</i>-value requires a null hypothesis, a test s=
tatistic (together with deciding whether the researcher is performing a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-tailed_test" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"One-tailed test">one-tailed test</a> or a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-tailed_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Two-tail=
ed test">two-tailed test</a>), and data. Even though computing the test sta=
tistic on given data may be easy, computing the sampling distribution under=
 the null hypothesis, and then computing its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cumulative_distribution_function" title=3D"Cumulative distributi=
on function">cumulative distribution function</a> (CDF) is often a difficul=
t problem. Today, this computation is done using statistical software, ofte=
n via numeric methods (rather than exact formulae), but, in the early and m=
id 20th century, this was instead done via tables of values, and one interp=
olated or extrapolated <i>p</i>-values from these discrete values<sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references t=
o reliable sources. (March 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>. Ra=
ther than using a table of <i>p</i>-values, Fisher instead inverted the CDF=
, publishing a list of values of the test statistic for given fixed <i>p</i=
>-values; this corresponds to computing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Quantile_function" title=3D"Quantile function">quantile function<=
/a> (inverse CDF).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Example">Example</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DP-value&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Example"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checking_whether_a_c=
oin_is_fair" title=3D"Checking whether a coin is fair">Checking whether a c=
oin is fair</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Testing_the_fairness_of_a_c=
oin">Testing the fairness of a coin</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DP-value&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Edit section: Testing the fairness of a coin"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As an example of a statistical test, an experiment is performed to deter=
mine whether a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coin_flipping" titl=
e=3D"Coin flipping">coin flip</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fair_coin" title=3D"Fair coin">fair</a> (equal chance of landing heads o=
r tails) or unfairly biased (one outcome being more likely than the other).
</p><p>Suppose that the experimental results show the coin turning up heads=
 14 times out of 20 total flips. The full data <span class=3D"mwe-math-elem=
ent mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math=
-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/199=
8/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle X}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>X</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/68baa052181f707c662844a465bfeeb135e82bab" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.98ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle X}">=
</span> would be a sequence of twenty times the symbol "H" or "T". The stat=
istic on which one might focus could be the total number <span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inlin=
e mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle T}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>T</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle T}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ec7200acd984a1d3a3d7dc455e262fbe54f7f6e0" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.636ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle T}"=
></span> of heads. The null hypothesis is that the coin is fair, and coin t=
osses are independent of one another. If a right-tailed test is considered,=
 which would be the case if one is actually interested in the possibility t=
hat the coin is biased towards falling heads, then the <i>p</i>-value of th=
is result is the chance of a fair coin landing on heads <i>at least</i> 14 =
times out of 20 flips. That probability can be computed from <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_coefficient" title=3D"Binomial coeffici=
ent">binomial coefficients</a> as
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}&amp;\Pr(14{\text{ heads}})+\Pr(15{\text{ heads}})+\cdots=
 +\Pr(20{\text{ heads}})\\&amp;=3D{\frac {1}{2^{20}}}\left[{\binom {20}{14}=
}+{\binom {20}{15}}+\cdots +{\binom {20}{20}}\right]=3D{\frac {60\,460}{1\,=
