    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\begin{align=
ed}&amp;\Pr(14{\text{ heads}})+\Pr(15{\text{ heads}})+\cdots +\Pr(20{\text{=
 heads}})\\&amp;=3D{\frac {1}{2^{20}}}\left[{\binom {20}{14}}+{\binom {20}{=
15}}+\cdots +{\binom {20}{20}}\right]=3D{\frac {60\,460}{1\,048\,576}}\appr=
ox 0.058.\end{aligned}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/1f2eebd3ba4473859aaacc3235a3929b3bf3b2bb" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -4.005ex; width:60.937ex; height:9.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
begin{aligned}&amp;\Pr(14{\text{ heads}})+\Pr(15{\text{ heads}})+\cdots +\P=
r(20{\text{ heads}})\\&amp;=3D{\frac {1}{2^{20}}}\left[{\binom {20}{14}}+{\=
binom {20}{15}}+\cdots +{\binom {20}{20}}\right]=3D{\frac {60\,460}{1\,048\=
,576}}\approx 0.058.\end{aligned}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This probability is the <i>p</i>-value, considering only extreme results=
 that favor heads. This is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/One-_and_two-tailed_tests" title=3D"One- and two-tailed tests">one-tailed=
 test</a>. However, one might be interested in deviations in either directi=
on, favoring either heads or tails. The two-tailed <i>p</i>-value, which co=
nsiders deviations favoring either heads or tails, may instead be calculate=
d. As the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" t=
itle=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial distribution</a> is symmetrical for=
 a fair coin, the two-sided <i>p</i>-value is simply twice the above calcul=
ated single-sided <i>p</i>-value: the two-sided <i>p</i>-value is 0.115.
</p><p>In the above example:
</p>
<ul><li>Null hypothesis (<i>H</i><sub>0</sub>): The coin is fair, with Pr(h=
eads) =3D 0.5.</li>
<li>Test statistic: Number of heads.</li>
<li>Alpha level (designated threshold of significance): 0.05.</li>
<li>Observation <i>O</i>: 14 heads out of 20 flips.</li>
<li>Two-tailed <i>p</i>-value of observation <i>O</i> given <i>H</i><sub>0<=
/sub> =3D 2 =C3=97 min(Pr(no. of heads =E2=89=A5&nbsp;14&nbsp;heads), Pr(no=
. of heads =E2=89=A4&nbsp;14&nbsp;heads)) =3D 2 =C3=97 min(0.058, 0.978) =
=3D 2&nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;0.058 =3D 0.115.</li></ul>
<p>The Pr(no. of heads =E2=89=A4&nbsp;14&nbsp;heads) =3D 1 =E2=88=92 Pr(no.=
 of heads =E2=89=A5&nbsp;14&nbsp;heads) + Pr(no. of head =3D 14) =3D 1 =E2=
=88=92 0.058 + 0.036 =3D 0.978; however, the symmetry of this binomial dist=
ribution makes it an unnecessary computation to find the smaller of the two=
 probabilities. Here, the calculated <i>p</i>-value exceeds 0.05, meaning t=
hat the data falls within the range of what would happen 95% of the time, i=
f the coin were fair. Hence, the null hypothesis is not rejected at the 0.0=
5 level.
</p><p>However, had one more head been obtained, the resulting <i>p</i>-val=
ue (two-tailed) would have been 0.0414&nbsp;(4.14%), in which case the null=
 hypothesis would be rejected at the 0.05 level.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Optional_stopping">Optional=
 stopping</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DP-=
value&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Optional s=
topping"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Optional_stopping"></span>
</p><p>The difference between the two meanings of "extreme" appear when we =
consider a sequential hypothesis testing, or optional stopping, for the fai=
rness of the coin. In general, optional stopping changes how p-value is cal=
culated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_n=
ote-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Suppose we design the experiment as follows:
</p>
<ul><li>Flip the coin twice. If both comes up heads or tails, end the exper=
iment.</li>
<li>Else, flip the coin 4 more times.</li></ul>
<p>This experiment has 7 types of outcomes: 2&nbsp;heads, 2&nbsp;tails, 5&n=
bsp;heads 1&nbsp;tail,&nbsp;..., 1&nbsp;head 5&nbsp;tails. We now calculate=
 the <i>p</i>-value of the "3&nbsp;heads 3&nbsp;tails" outcome.
</p><p>If we use the test statistic #<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-ma=
th-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a1=
1y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Mat=
hML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\text{heads}}/{\text{tails}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>heads</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>tails</mtext>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\text{heads}=
}/{\text{tails}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/071c710443eb26185a738cceccad5258a7fe61a6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:11.136ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
text{heads}}/{\text{tails}}}"></span>, then under the null hypothesis (i.e.=
 #<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"m=
we-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math =
xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\te=
xt{heads}}\leq 3}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>heads</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=89=A4<!-- =E2=89=A4 --></mo>
        <mn>3</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\text{heads}=
}\leq 3}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/01137377c1a04d56b97a850efd39bc5c384539e1" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:9.957ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\t=
ext{heads}}\leq 3}"></span>) the two-sided <i>p</i>-value is exactly equal =
to 1, and both the one-sided left-tail p-value and the one-sided right-tail=
 <i>p</i>-value are exactly equal to <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-ma=
th-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a1=
1y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Mat=
hML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 19/32}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>19</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mn>32</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 19/32}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9f1d43f80af70442e5cb33d23e1be02525cd7916" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:5.812ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 19/=
32}"></span>.
</p><p>If we consider every outcome that has equal or lower probability tha=
n "3&nbsp;heads 3&nbsp;tails" as "at least as extreme", then the <i>p</i>-v=
alue is exactly <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle 1/2.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mn>2.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1/2.}</annota=
tion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0e15cf80ad635a94ab6b09444b44368fdf171fd9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:4.134ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1/2=
.}"></span>
</p><p>However, suppose we have planned to simply flip the coin 6&nbsp;time=
s no matter what happens, then the second definition of <i>p</i>-value woul=
d mean that the <i>p</i>-value of "3&nbsp;heads 3&nbsp;tails" is exactly 1.
</p><p>Thus, the "at least as extreme" definition of <i>p</i>-value is deep=
ly contextual and depends on what the experimenter <i>planned</i> to do eve=
n in situations that did not occur.
</p>
