file-height=3D"408"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Ronald_Fisher" title=3D"Ronald Fisher">Ronald Fisher</a> </figcaption></f=
igure>
<p><i>P</i>-value computations date back to the 1700s, where they were comp=
uted for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_sex_ratio" titl=
e=3D"Human sex ratio">human sex ratio</a> at birth, and used to compute sta=
tistical significance compared to the null hypothesis of equal probability =
of male and female births.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Arbuthnot" title=3D"John Arbuthnot=
">John Arbuthnot</a> studied this question in 1710,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_n=
ote-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Conover1999_34-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-Conover1999-34=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sprent1989_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-Sprent1989-35"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and examined birth records=
 in London for each of the 82 years from 1629 to 1710. In every year, the n=
umber of males born in London exceeded the number of females. Considering m=
ore male or more female births as equally likely, the probability of the ob=
served outcome is 1/2<sup>82</sup>, or about 1 in 4,836,000,000,000,000,000=
,000,000; in modern terms, the <i>p</i>-value. This is vanishingly small, l=
eading Arbuthnot to conclude that this was not due to chance, but to divine=
 providence: "From whence it follows, that it is Art, not Chance, that gove=
rns." In modern terms, he rejected the null hypothesis of equally likely ma=
le and female births at the <i>p</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;1/2<sup>82</sup> signifi=
cance level. This and other work by Arbuthnot is credited as "=E2=80=A6 the=
 first use of significance tests =E2=80=A6"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bellhouse200=
1_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-valu=
e#cite_note-Bellhouse2001-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the first example of reasoning ab=
out statistical significance,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hald1998_38-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-Hald199=
8-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> and "=E2=80=A6 perhaps the first published report of a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-parametric_test" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Non-parametric test">nonparametric test</a> =E2=80=A6",<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Conover1999_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-Conover1999-34"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> specifica=
lly the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign_test" title=3D"Sign t=
est">sign test</a>; see details at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Sign_test#History" title=3D"Sign test">Sign test =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a>.
</p><p>The same question was later addressed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-Simon Laplace">Pierre-S=
imon Laplace</a>, who instead used a <i>parametric</i> test, modeling the n=
umber of male births with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomi=
al_distribution" title=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial distribution</a>:=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>In the 1770s Laplace con=
sidered the statistics of almost half a million births. The statistics show=
ed an excess of boys compared to girls. He concluded by calculation of a <i=
>p</i>-value that the excess was a real, but unexplained, effect.</p></bloc=
kquote>
<p>The <i>p</i>-value was first formally introduced by <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" title=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a>,=
 in his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson%27s_chi-squared_te=
st" title=3D"Pearson's chi-squared test">Pearson's chi-squared test</a>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Pearson1900_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-Pearson1900-40"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> using th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_distribution" title=
=3D"Chi-squared distribution">chi-squared distribution</a> and notated as c=
apital P.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pearson1900_40-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-Pearson1900-40"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> The <i>p</i>-values for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
hi-squared_distribution" title=3D"Chi-squared distribution">chi-squared dis=
tribution</a> (for various values of =CF=87<sup>2</sup> and degrees of free=
dom), now notated as <i>P,</i> were calculated in (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/P-value#CITEREFElderton1902">Elderton 1902</a>), collected=
 in (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#CITEREFPearson1914">P=
earson 1914</a>, pp.&nbsp;xxxi=E2=80=93xxxiii, 26=E2=80=9328, Table XII).
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_Fisher" title=3D"Ron=
ald Fisher">Ronald Fisher</a> formalized and popularized the use of the <i>=
p</i>-value in statistics,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/P-value#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> with it playing a central role in his=
 approach to the subject.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In his=
 highly influential book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statis=
tical_Methods_for_Research_Workers" title=3D"Statistical Methods for Resear=
ch Workers">Statistical Methods for Research Workers</a></i> (1925), Fisher=
 proposed the level <i>p</i> =3D 0.05, or a 1 in 20 chance of being exceede=
d by chance, as a limit for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statis=
tical_significance" title=3D"Statistical significance">statistical signific=
ance</a>, and applied this to a normal distribution (as a two-tailed test),=
 thus yielding the rule of two standard deviations (on a normal distributio=
n) for statistical significance (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/68%E2%80%9395%E2%80%9399.7_rule" title=3D"68=E2=80=9395=E2=80=9399.7 rul=
e">68=E2=80=9395=E2=80=9399.7 rule</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFisher1=
92547Chapter_[httppsychclassicsyorkucaFisherMethodschap3htm_III._Distributi=
ons]_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-v=
alue#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFisher192547Chapter_[httppsychclassicsyorkucaFisherM=
ethodschap3htm_III._Distributions]-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_no=
te-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 3<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDallal2012Note_31:_[httpw=
wwjerrydallalcomLHSPp05htm_Why_P=3D0.05?]_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDallal2012Note_=
31:_[httpwwwjerrydallalcomLHSPp05htm_Why_P=3D0.05?]-46"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>He then computed a table of values, similar to Elderton but, importa=
ntly, reversed the roles of =CF=87<sup>2</sup> and <i>p.</i> That is, rathe=
r than computing <i>p</i> for different values of =CF=87<sup>2</sup> (and d=
egrees of freedom <i>n</i>), he computed values of =CF=87<sup>2</sup> that =
yield specified <i>p</i>-values, specifically 0.99, 0.98, 0.95, 0,90, 0.80,=
 0.70, 0.50, 0.30, 0.20, 0.10, 0.05, 0.02, and 0.01.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOO=
TNOTEFisher192578=E2=80=9379,_98Chapter_[httppsychclassicsyorkucaFisherMeth=
odschap4htm_IV._Tests_of_Goodness_of_Fit,_Independence_and_Homogeneity;_wit=
h_Table_of_=CF=87&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;],_[httppsychclassicsyorkucaFisher=
MethodstabIIIgif_Table_III._Table_of_=CF=87&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;]_47-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_n=
ote-FOOTNOTEFisher192578%E2%80%9379,_98Chapter_[httppsychclassicsyorkucaFis=
herMethodschap4htm_IV._Tests_of_Goodness_of_Fit,_Independence_and_Homogenei=
ty;_with_Table_of_%CF%87%3Csup%3E2%3C/sup%3E],_[httppsychclassicsyorkucaFis=
herMethodstabIIIgif_Table_III._Table_of_%CF%87%3Csup%3E2%3C/sup%3E]-47"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> That allowed computed values of =CF=87<sup>2</sup> to be compared =
against cutoffs and encouraged the use of <i>p</i>-values (especially 0.05,=
 0.02, and 0.01) as cutoffs, instead of computing and reporting <i>p</i>-va=
lues themselves. The same type of tables were then compiled in (<a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#CITEREFFisherYates1938">Fisher &amp; =
Yates 1938</a>), which cemented the approach.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDa=
llal2012Note_31:_[httpwwwjerrydallalcomLHSPp05htm_Why_P=3D0.05?]_46-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-=
FOOTNOTEDallal2012Note_31:_[httpwwwjerrydallalcomLHSPp05htm_Why_P=3D0.05?]-=
46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>As an illustration of the application of <i>p</i>-values to the desi=
gn and interpretation of experiments, in his following book <i><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Design_of_Experiments" title=3D"The Design=
 of Experiments">The Design of Experiments</a></i> (1935), Fisher presented=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lady_tasting_tea" title=3D"La=
dy tasting tea">lady tasting tea</a> experiment,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
EFisher1971II._The_Principles_of_Experimentation,_Illustrated_by_a_Psycho-p=
hysical_Experiment_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFisher1971II._The_Principles_of_Experi=
mentation,_Illustrated_by_a_Psycho-physical_Experiment-48"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> whic=
h is the archetypal example of the <i>p</i>-value.
</p><p>To evaluate a lady's claim that she (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Muriel_Bristol" title=3D"Muriel Bristol">Muriel Bristol</a>) coul=
d distinguish by taste how tea is prepared (first adding the milk to the cu=
p, then the tea, or first tea, then milk), she was sequentially presented w=
ith 8 cups: 4 prepared one way, 4 prepared the other, and asked to determin=
e the preparation of each cup (knowing that there were 4 of each). In that =
case, the null hypothesis was that she had no special ability, the test was=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher%27s_exact_test" title=3D"F=
isher's exact test">Fisher's exact test</a>, and the <i>p</i>-value was <sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 1/{\binom=
 {8}{4}}=3D1/70\approx 0.014,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-OPEN">
              <mo maxsize=3D"2.047em" minsize=3D"2.047em">(</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mfrac linethickness=3D"0">
              <mn>8</mn>
              <mn>4</mn>
            </mfrac>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-CLOSE">
              <mo maxsize=3D"2.047em" minsize=3D"2.047em">)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mn>70</mn>
        <mo>=E2=89=88<!-- =E2=89=88 --></mo>
        <mn>0.014</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1/{\binom {8}=
{4}}=3D1/70\approx 0.014,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/fe167ba2c3042185ee930dbbeefaf3c79104f7a3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.505ex; width:23.699ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1/=
{\binom {8}{4}}=3D1/70\approx 0.014,}"></span> so Fisher was willing to rej=
ect the null hypothesis (consider the outcome highly unlikely to be due to =
chance) if all were classified correctly. (In the actual experiment, Bristo=
l correctly classified all 8 cups.)
</p><p>Fisher reiterated the <i>p</i> =3D 0.05 threshold and explained its =
rationale, stating:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFisher1971Section_7._The_Tes=
t_of_Significance_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFisher1971Section_7._The_Test_of_Signif=
icance-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>It is usual and convenie=
nt for experimenters to take 5 per cent as a standard level of significance=
, in the sense that they are prepared to ignore all results which fail to r=
each this standard, and, by this means, to eliminate from further discussio=
n the greater part of the fluctuations which chance causes have introduced =
into their experimental results.</p></blockquote>
<p>He also applies this threshold to the design of experiments, noting that=
 had only 6 cups been presented (3 of each), a perfect classification would=
 have only yielded a <i>p</i>-value of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-=
math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-=
a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/M=
athML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 1/{\binom {6}{3}}=3D1/20=3D0.05,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-OPEN">
              <mo maxsize=3D"2.047em" minsize=3D"2.047em">(</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mfrac linethickness=3D"0">
              <mn>6</mn>
              <mn>3</mn>
            </mfrac>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-CLOSE">
              <mo maxsize=3D"2.047em" minsize=3D"2.047em">)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mn>20</mn>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>0.05</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1/{\binom {6}=
{3}}=3D1/20=3D0.05,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a9d5227d387fd8c3781366f6c578a3229307f547" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.505ex; width:22.536ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1/=
{\binom {6}{3}}=3D1/20=3D0.05,}"></span> which would not have met this leve=
l of significance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFisher1971Section_7._The_Test=
_of_Significance_49-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFisher1971Section_7._The_Test_of_Signifi=
cance-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Fisher also underlined the interpretation of <i>p,</i=
> as the long-run proportion of values at least as extreme as the data, ass=
uming the null hypothesis is true.
</p><p>In later editions, Fisher explicitly contrasted the use of the <i>p<=
/i>-value for statistical inference in science with the Neyman=E2=80=93Pear=
son method, which he terms "Acceptance Procedures".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOT=
NOTEFisher1971Section_12.1_Scientific_Inference_and_Acceptance_Procedures_5=
0-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#c=
ite_note-FOOTNOTEFisher1971Section_12.1_Scientific_Inference_and_Acceptance=
_Procedures-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Fisher emphasizes that while fixed levels such =
as 5%, 2%, and 1% are convenient, the exact <i>p</i>-value can be used, and=
 the strength of evidence can and will be revised with further experimentat=
ion. In contrast, decision procedures require a clear-cut decision, yieldin=
g an irreversible action, and the procedure is based on costs of error, whi=
ch, he argues, are inapplicable to scientific research.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Related_indices">Related in=
dices</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DP-valu=
e&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Related indice=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>The <i>E-value</i> can refer to two concepts, both of which are related =
to the p-value and both of which play a role in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Multiple_comparisons" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multiple=
 comparisons">multiple testing</a>. First, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/E-values" title=3D"E-values">it corresponds to a generic, more rob=
ust alternative to the p-value</a> that can deal with <i>optional continuat=
ion</i> of experiments. Second, it is also used to abbreviate "expect value=
", which is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_expect=
ation" title=3D"Conditional expectation">expected</a> number of times that =
one expects to obtain a test statistic at least as extreme as the one that =
was actually observed if one assumes that the null hypothesis is true.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/P-value#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This expect-value is the product of =
the number of tests and the <i>p</i>-value.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q-value_(statistics)" t=
itle=3D"Q-value (statistics)"><i>q</i>-value</a> is the analog of the <i>p<=
/i>-value with respect to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fals=
e_discovery_rate#Related_concepts" title=3D"False discovery rate">positive =
false discovery rate</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is =
used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_comparisons_probl=
em" title=3D"Multiple comparisons problem">multiple hypothesis testing</a> =
to maintain statistical power while minimizing the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/False_positive_rate" title=3D"False positive rate">false p=
ositive rate</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_of_Directio=
n" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Probability of Direction">Probability of =
Direction (<i>pd</i>)</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
ayesian_statistics" title=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian</a> numerical eq=
uivalent of the <i>p</i>-value.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-makowski2019indices_54-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite=
_note-makowski2019indices-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It corresponds to the proportion =
of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" titl=
e=3D"Posterior probability">posterior distribution</a> that is of the media=
n's sign, typically varying between 50% and 100%, and representing the cert=
ainty with which an effect is positive or negative.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSecond-gener=
ation_p-values&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Se=
cond-generation p-values (page does not exist)">Second-generation p-values<=
/a> extend the concept of p-values by not considering extremely small, prac=
tically irrelevant <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effect_size" ti=
tle=3D"Effect size">effect sizes</a> as significant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value#cite_=
note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
